items.description:
This iconic château was built as a hunting lodge for Francis I (1494 - 1547) of France. Taking 28 years to build (1519 - 1547), Francis I only spent about seven weeks total at the lodge before his death. From what I remember, it is no longer decorated on the inside - the interior "walls" have been removed exposing the stone structure. I believe there are plans to restore the interiors at some point. The château is known for the central double-helix staircase: allowing people to ascend and descend the stairs without ever meeting. It has been suggested that it was designed by Leonardo DaVinci, but no proof has been found. Francis' "everyday" home was the Royal Château of Blois. If you take the train, this is just a couple blocks from the Blois train station.

Getting to

It is possible to get from Paris to the château via train. It is a 90 minute train ride from Paris to Blois. At Blois, you have to catch the infrequent bus or get a taxi for the 25 minute ride through the countryside and all the tiny villages to the château. It is actually rather scary as the bus slows only slightly as it passes between houses literally built up to the end of the road. Don't expect to hop off the train and directly onto the bus!!! First, trains don't run per scheduled and you're likely to arrive later than expected. Second, it is unlikely there's a bus leaving when you need it - this is a tiny town and you may have to wait 1-2 hours. I found it "challenging" to figure out which bus to take and ended up taking a taxi after wandering around the town of Blois. Note: the "bathroom" at the Blois train station was the worst I've ever encountered - basically an unlit, concrete room with a thin metal door. One would have to be absolutely desperate to use it. Returning from Chambord, you need to make sure the catch the last bus to Blois - around 4:00 p.m. If you don't make it, I don't know what you'd do: I did not see any taxi stands or Ubers waiting around. There are no motels, restaurants, gas stations, etc. in the area. Once back in Blois, you need to wait for your train back to Paris. For all the reasons above, I highly recommend that you take a private tour or private car to Chambord: you'll spend more time viewing and less time waiting. Depending upon your mood, you can also arrange to get there early to watch the sunrise or stay later for the sunset. You can also join a tour bus. I'd recommend one that starts in Paris vs. Blois. As mentioned, your train may be later and you could miss your connection if you don't make it to Blois in time. There are hotels in Blois. I would caution that I didn't see any taxis during the 2-3 hours I walked around Blois.
